#ğŸš© How to Spot a Predatory Publisher
â— Red Flags (aka the "Tells")
1. Aggressive Email Solicitation

â€œDear esteemed researcher, we read your excellent paper in [journal you never published in] and would love for you to submit your latest work...â€
Be wary of flattering emails that sound generic or overly enthusiastic.

2. No Peer Review or Unrealistically Fast Turnaround
ğŸ“… If they promise peer review in 2 days, it's not real peer review.
Legit journals take timeâ€”weeks or months.

3. Vague or Missing Editorial Board
ğŸ‘€ Check the journalâ€™s editorial board. Are there actual experts listed? Can you verify their credentials or affiliations?
âŒ If there are no names or fake-looking profiles, big red flag.

4. Poor Website Quality
ğŸ–¥ï¸ Bad grammar, broken links, fuzzy logos, or an outdated design = low effort = low credibility.
Professional, well-maintained sites are the norm for reputable journals.

5. Article Processing Charges (APCs) that Arenâ€™t Clearly Stated
ğŸ’¸ Hidden fees or surprise charges after acceptance? Thatâ€™s a predatory move.
Good journals are upfront about costsâ€”if any.

6. Indexing Claims that Donâ€™t Add Up
ğŸ” They might say theyâ€™re in Scopus or Web of Scienceâ€”but are they really?
 Cross-check in the actual database (not just on the journalâ€™s site).
Check DOAJ for legitimate open access journals.

7. Fake Impact Factors
ğŸ“ˆ Predatory journals sometimes cite made-up metrics (e.g., â€œGlobal Impact Factorâ€) instead of real ones like Clarivateâ€™s Journal Impact Factor.
Look for legit metrics from credible sources.

8. Poor Quality or Irrelevant Articles
ğŸ“ If past articles seem unrelated, shallow, or clearly unedited, steer clear.
A quick browse can reveal a lot.
---
âœ… What to Look For Instead
Indexed in DOAJ,  Scopus, or Web of Science

Transparent peer-review process

Clear author guidelines and ethical policies

Recognizable, reputable publisher (e.g., Springer, Wiley, Elsevier, university press)

Clear APC info (or none at all, in the case of diamond open access)
