###About Scholaris
Western Libraries has joined the new national shared repository service, Scholaris. This means that the institutional repository, Scholarship@Western will be migrating to a new platform. It will move from its current bepress/Digital Commons platform to a Scholaris-hosted DSpace instance, supported by Scholars Portal by June 30, 2025.

The repository will be re-branded as Western Scholaris and users will notice some changes as part of the migration process. For example, there will be a new streamlined interface with a refined collections hierarchy.

With this move, the repositoryâ€™s scope will be more tightly focused on making open access content publicly available. This means that some metadata-only content will not be migrated. Other content, such as image archives or digital scholarship projects, will be moved to platforms other than DSpace. To facilitate these various moves, that content will remain on the current Scholarship@Western platform for the next year or so, likely until early 2026.

If you are an administrator of a collection in the current Scholarship@Western platform, please continue that work as-is. As we learn more and get closer to the migration date, one of the migration team members will be in touch with more specific information about how your project will be affected.

We will be sharing additional project milestones and updates as we move closer to our go live date. We appreciate your support and patience during this transition.

Please direct any questions, comments, or concerns about the repository migration to the Research & Scholarly Communications Team at rsclib@uwo.ca.
#Sharing via Social Media Sites

ğŸ“£ Youâ€™re proud of your work and want to share it with the world. Social media can be a powerful way to boost visibilityâ€”but there are a few things to know first.
---
### ğŸ”— As a colleague of mine likes to say:  
**â€œLinks are free! (At least... they havenâ€™t monetized them yet.)â€**

You are absolutely allowed to share **article metadata** on social media platforms like Twitter/X, LinkedIn, Mastodon, BLuesky, Threads, or even Instagram:

âœ… Title
âœ… Author(s)
âœ… Journal name
âœ… DOI or permalink

**Sharing a link** to your article (or its version in a repository) helps readers find it *legally and ethically*.
---
### ğŸ“° What about sharing the article itself?

 âœ… If itâ€™s in an **Open Access journal**, go ahead and share the full-text link (or PDF if the licence allows).
-âœ… If your article is in a **repository**, you can safely share the link to the **accepted manuscript** or **preprint**â€”check the version you uploaded!

- âš ï¸ If itâ€™s the **final publisher PDF** from a subscription journalâ€”hold up! That might break copyright.

Check the publisherâ€™s sharing policy or use [JISC open policy finder](https://openpolicyfinder.jisc.ac.uk/) to confirm what version you can legally post. or ask you friendly neighbourhood librarian.
---
### âš ï¸ What about ResearchGate or Academia.edu?

- These are **academic social networks**, not repositories.
- âŒ They are **not considered Open Access** by most funders.
- âŒ They are **for-profit** platforms that may monetize your data and your PDFs.
- âš ï¸ Many publishers have issued takedown notices for unauthorized uploads.

ğŸ‘‹ So post your **metadata and links**, not your final PDFs.

---
